## Todo file format

All todo data is stored inside a single text file.

The format is the markup language described in the help applet,
and each todo note is a top-level meta note. For example:

> [x] Here is done task.
  [] A task yet to be completed.
  [created:2000-01-01 @foo @bar] Take the dog out.

Here is a complete list of attributes that top-level meta blocks
can have:

> [ x
    #1
    pin
    hide
    @foo
    track:3
    due:2000-01-24
    created:2000-01-24
  ]
    The task body.

Here is the explanation of each attribute:

|-------------------------------------------------
| x
| Task is marked as completed.
|-------------------------------------------------
| \#1
| Task has priority 1.
|-------------------------------------------------
| pin
| A marker used for sorting and filtering.
|-------------------------------------------------
| \@foo
| Task has tag foo.
|-------------------------------------------------
| track: 3
| Task has an entry in the time tracker that
  is identified by the number 3.
|-------------------------------------------------
| due: 2000-01-24
| Task has a due date. The date format follows
  the ISO 8601 spec: year-month-day.
|-------------------------------------------------
| created: 2000-01-24
| Date of creation in ISO format.
|-------------------------------------------------
| hide
| Only these filter expressions can evaluate to
  true when applied to hidden tasks:

  1. `*
  2. `hide
  3. `hide & expr
|-------------------------------------------------

## Filters and kanban boards

With each deck you can specify a comma separated list of 
filter expressions. For each filter expression there will
be 1 column of tasks in the main view. A given task will
go into the first column starting from the left for which
it passes the given filter.
